Description: Fragment of a larger seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows two rows of basketry coil on one side and another row at a second side, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and a lit of a basket. The section is triangular. The flat front shows an impression of a larger oval scarab-like seal. Visible is a nfr-sign at the left, further right a seated baboon with a moon crescent above his head, facing to the left. Further right a lying ram at the right side, facing to the left, wearing the atef crown with uraei. Three hieroglyphs above his rear, difficult to identify.
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
